Estimating family-planning indicators with FPEM

Herb Susmann

10/4/2021

Load the tidyverse family of packages:

library(tidyverse)

First, install the fpemlocal package from Github:

remotes::install_github("AlkemaLab/fpemlocal")

Now we can load the package:

library(fpemlocal)

The package identifies countries by a numeric code. The divisions data frame lists all the countries and their associated codes:

divisions %>%
  select(division_numeric_code, name_country)
## # A tibble: 232  2
##    division_numeric_code name_country       
##                    <dbl> <chr>              
##  1                     4 Afghanistan        
##  2                     8 Albania            
##  3                    12 Algeria            
##  4                    16 American Samoa     
##  5                    20 Andorra            
##  6                    24 Angola             
##  7                   660 Anguilla           
##  8                    28 Antigua and Barbuda
##  9                    32 Argentina          
## 10                    51 Armenia            
## #  with 222 more rows

Lets search for one specific country:

divisions %>%
  filter(name_country == "Bangladesh") %>%
  select(division_numeric_code, name_country)
## # A tibble: 1  2
##   division_numeric_code name_country
##                   <dbl> <chr>       
## 1                    50 Bangladesh

Now that we know the code, we can use the fit_fp_c function to fit FPEM. We specify to use data from in-union women, and to estimate from 1970 to 2030:

fit <- fit_fp_c(
  division_numeric_code = 50,
  is_in_union = "Y",
  first_year = 1970,
  last_year = 2030
)

Once we have the fit, we can generate a summary for each indicator using the calc_fp_c function:

results <- calc_fp_c(fit)

Finally, can plot the results. Here are the results for the modern contraceptive use indicator:

plot_fp_c(
  fit,
  results,
  indicators = c("contraceptive_use_modern")
)
## $Y
## $Y$contraceptive_use_modern

Traditional contraceptive use:

plot_fp_c(
  fit,
  results,
  indicators = c("contraceptive_use_traditional")
)
## $Y
## $Y$contraceptive_use_traditional

Unmet need for modern contraceptives:

plot_fp_c(
  fit,
  results,
  indicators = c("unmet_need_modern")
)
## $Y
## $Y$unmet_need_modern
